The Protobuf plugin assumes Protobuf files (*.proto) are organized in the same way as Java source files, in sourceSets. The Protobuf files of a sourceSet are compiled in a single protoc run, and the generated files are added to the input of the Java compilation run of that sourceSet ().

    sourceSets {
        main {
            java {
                srcDirs &#39;build/generated/source/proto/main/grpc&#39;
                srcDirs &#39;build/generated/source/proto/main/java&#39;
            }
        }
    }

For me, first of all a problem (in Eclipse) was using single quotes around `$` variables. My working `gradle.build` to compile proto files to Java classes in a custom directory was this:

    protobuf {
        protoc { artifact = &quot;com.google.protobuf:protoc:${protocVersion}&quot; }
        plugins {
            grpc { artifact = &quot;io.grpc:protoc-gen-grpc-java:${grpcVersion}&quot; }
        }
      	generatedFilesBaseDir = &quot;$projectDir/gensrc&quot;
        generateProtoTasks {
            all()*.plugins { grpc {} }
        }
    }
    
    // Inform IDEs like IntelliJ IDEA, Eclipse or NetBeans about the generated code.
    sourceSets {
        main {
            java {
                srcDirs &quot;${protobuf.generatedFilesBaseDir}/main/java&quot;
                srcDirs &quot;${protobuf.generatedFilesBaseDir}/main/grpc&quot;
            }
        }
    }

Then Eclipse could not tell these were source files. I had to refresh the project:

[![refresh][1]][1]

Then add the custom files to the build path

[![build path][2]][2]


  [1]: https://i.stack.imgur.com/iD4l8.png
  [2]: https://i.stack.imgur.com/ykZHu.png

First things to do is create the `@Entity` annotated classes according to the schema of the database. That is, each `@Entity` reflects a table.

When you have these classes then create the `@Database` annotated class with all of the `@Entity` annotated classes in the list of entities of the entities parameter of the `@Database` annotation. You then compile (successfully) and the java(generated) will have a class named the same as the @Database annotated class BUT suffixed with `_Impl`. Within this class there will be a method called `createAllTables`. This will contain the **EXACT** SQL for the creation of the tables. **It is important that the database schema matches this SQL** (otherwise you will get an exception saying that the schema&#39;s do not match with the message detailing what Room expected and what was actually found).

If there are differences then you need to convert the database accordingly (it is suggested that you use the generated SQL to create new tables, load the new tables with the data from the original tables, then rename (or if confident drop them) original tables and then rename the new tables to the original names). You will then have a database with the schema according to Room&#39;s expectations.

You can then create an assets folder/directory in the project and copy the database into that folder and then add the `createFromAsset` method to the @Database. Room will copy the database from the assets folder via this method.

However, before running you would probably want to create some `@Dao` annotated interfaces (or abstract classes which have the advantage of allowing methods with bodies which can be useful) with methods appropriate for your project.

You may find this helpful:-

- https://stackoverflow.com/questions/70580333/move-data-from-sqlite-database-file-to-room/70584194#70584194

----

You say

&gt; .sql file, because I didn&#39;t establish to convert it to a .db file

The extension doesn&#39;t matter (as long as it&#39;s a valid file name) and the full file name is specified as the parameter passed to the `createFromAsset` method. 


----

**Working Example**

----

**The existing database**

For this example the existing database consists of 3 tables:-

- the **user** table with 3 columns:-
    - **userid** (INTEGER PRIMARY KEY NOT NULL) i.e. unique identifier
    - **username** a textual type **BUT** defined using a type as ***NOTAROOMKNOWNTYPE*** (a type as it says that Room will not allow)
    - **useremail** with a type of TEXT

- the **meeting** table with 4 columns:-
    - **meetingid** (again INTEGER PRIMARY KEY NOT NULL)
    - **meetingname** with a type of TEXT
    - **startdatetime** with a type of integer (intended for a time stamp)
    - **enddatetime** with a type of integer (again timestamp)

- the **usermeetingmap** table with 2 columns to enable a many-many relationship between user and meeting (a user can attend many meetings and a meeting can have many users)
    - **usermap** with a type of LONG (not supported/known by room)
    - **meetingmap** likewise.

The following is the SQL used to create the tables, populate them with some data and also to extract the data:-

