**Step 1 - Create the `@Entity` annotated classes**

- **Note** I suggest writing 1 @Entity annotated class at a time, then compiling (CTRL + F9) to see if there are an reported issues.
    - You could also inspect the generated java and make notes of any discrepancies between the existing database and the room database.

**Step 1.1 Create the User class**

From the above we know that the User table should have 3 columns, the primary key being the **userid** column. **Room** requires that all tables have a primary key (it does not support WITHOUT ROWID tables).

So the **User** class could be:-

    @Entity
    class User {
        @PrimaryKey
        Long userid=null;
        String username; /* NOTE CANNOT USE NOTAROOMKNOWNTYPE as we know it&#39;s a TEXT type then java String type */
        String useremail;
    }

To test this the **`@Database`** annotated class will now be added to suit this single table e.g.:-

    @Database( entities = {User.class}, exportSchema = false, version = 1)
    abstract class TheDatabase extends RoomDatabase {
    }

If the project is compiled (successfully i.e. it is suggested that you ALWAYS check the build log) then you can compare the SQL of the User table that Room expects e.g. :-

[![enter image description here][2]][2]

In this case we compare the two (Room SQL with Original SQL/schema):-

    CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS `User` (`userid` INTEGER, `username` TEXT, `useremail` TEXT, PRIMARY KEY(`userid`))

and 
    CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS user (userid INTEGER,username NOTAROOMKNOWNTYPE,useremail TEXT,PRIMARY KEY (userid));

- They differ
    - the **username** column has TEXT v NOTAROOMKNOWNTYPE. **THIS MUST BE CHANGED TO SUIT ROOM** 

    - note that Room encloses all table/column names in `&#39;s that just ensures that the names are taken as names.

**Step 1.2 Meeting class** first attempt:-

    @Entity
    class Meeting {
        @PrimaryKey
        Long meetingid=null;
        String meetingname;
        long startdatetime;
        long enddatetime;
    }

Then amend the **TheDatabase** to include the new entity:-

    @Database( entities = {User.class,Meeting.class}, exportSchema = false, version = 1)

Again compare SQL (Room v original):-

    CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS `Meeting` (`meetingid` INTEGER, `meetingname` TEXT, `startdatetime` INTEGER NOT NULL, `enddatetime` INTEGER NOT NULL, PRIMARY KEY(`meetingid`))

    CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS meeting (meetingid INTEGER,meetingname TEXT,startdatetime integer,enddatetime integer,PRIMARY KEY (meetingid));

- **There is a difference** Room has added the NOT NULL constraint for the startdatetime and enddatetime columns. Room would not accept this. So something has to be changed.

    - for primitives (long in this case) Room will always add a NOT NULL constraint. A way around this is to instead use an Object. In this case Long instead of Long.

So the **Meeting** class can be changed to :-

    @Entity
    class Meeting {
        @PrimaryKey
        Long meetingid=null;
        String meetingname;
        Long startdatetime;
        Long enddatedate;
    }

And after Compiling then Room&#39;s generated SQL is now:-

    CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS `Meeting` (`meetingid` INTEGER, `meetingname` TEXT, `startdatetime` INTEGER, `enddatetime` INTEGER, PRIMARY KEY(`meetingid`))


**Step 1.3 UserMeetingMap class**

    @Entity(
            /* @Primary can only be used to annotated a single member/column as a composite primary key is required then */
            primaryKeys = {&quot;usermap&quot;,&quot;meetingmap&quot;},
