As can be seen the original has type LONG rather than INTEGER, **THIS MUST BE CHANGED**.


**STEP 2 Converting the original database**

Using the approach we can see that unless the database is converted that Room will reject the database as not being the expected database. As such, due to Room&#39;s requirements the original database **MUST BE ALTERED ACCORDINGLY**.

In summary the unacceptable ***NOTAROOMKNOWNTYPE*** must be changed to **TEXT** and the two occurrences of ***LONG*** must be changed to **INTEGER**.

The easiest way is to use an SQLite tool and:-

 1. Rename the original tables
 2. Create the new tables by copying the generated SQL (i.e. Room&#39;s expected tables)
 3. Per table, use INSERT INTO table SELECT * FROM original_table;
     1. Note that if using Foreign Keys (and not deferring or turning off foreign key support) then parent tables must be loaded before children. 
 1. Drop the original tables
 1. Optionally, but suggested, VACUUM
 1. Save the database


e.g. for this demo the following was used:-

    /* Just in case */
    DROP TABLE IF EXISTS original_usermeetingmap;
    DROP TABLE IF EXISTS original_user;
    DROP TABLE IF EXISTS original_meeting;
    ALTER TABLE user RENAME TO original_user;
    ALTER TABLE meeting RENAME TO original_meeting;
    ALTER TABLE usermeetingmap RENAME TO original_usermeetingmap;
    
    /* COPY ROOM GENERATE SQL HERE */
    CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS `User` (`userid` INTEGER, `username` TEXT, `useremail` TEXT, PRIMARY KEY(`userid`));
    CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS `Meeting` (`meetingid` INTEGER, `meetingname` TEXT, `startdatetime` INTEGER, `enddatetime` INTEGER, PRIMARY KEY(`meetingid`));
    CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS `UserMeetingMap` (`usermap` INTEGER NOT NULL, `meetingmap` INTEGER NOT NULL, PRIMARY KEY(`usermap`, `meetingmap`), FOREIGN KEY(`usermap`) REFERENCES `User`(`userid`) ON UPDATE CASCADE ON DELETE CASCADE , FOREIGN KEY(`meetingmap`) REFERENCES `Meeting`(`meetingid`) ON UPDATE CASCADE ON DELETE CASCADE );
    /* COPY THE DATA */
    INSERT INTO user SELECT * FROM original_user;
    INSERT INTO meeting SELECT * FROM original_meeting;
    INSERT INTO usermeetingmap SELECT * FROM original_usermeetingmap;
    /* JUST CHECKING */
    SELECT 
    	user.username,user.useremail, 
    	meeting.meetingname, 
    	datetime(meeting.startdatetime,&#39;unixepoch&#39;) AS starts,
    	datetime(meeting.enddatetime,&#39;unixepoch&#39;) AS ends FROM user 
    	JOIN usermeetingmap ON user.userid = usermeetingmap.usermap
    	JOIN meeting ON usermeetingmap.meetingmap = meeting.meetingid
    ORDER BY meetingid
    ;
    /* ONCE TESTED AS 100% OK uncomment following */
    /*DROP TABLE IF EXISTS original_usermeetingmap;*/
    /*DROP TABLE IF EXISTS original_user;*/
    /*DROP TABLE IF EXISTS original_meeting;*/
    /*VACUUM; to tidy up storage/free space */





**STEP 3 Preparing the Converted database**

Create the assets folder.

[![enter image description here][3]][3]

Copy the saved database, renaming if/as you want, into the assets folder (example where it has been renamed to the stupid file name `anything.anything`).

Amend the **TheDatabase** class (as one way) to provide a built (Rooms terminology) adatabase using the `createFromAsset` method e.g.

    @Database( entities = {User.class,Meeting.class,UserMeetingMap.class}, exportSchema = false, version = 1)
    abstract class TheDatabase extends RoomDatabase {
    
        private static volatile TheDatabase INSTANCE;
    
        public static TheDatabase getInstance(Context context) {
            if (INSTANCE==null) {
                INSTANCE = Room.databaseBuilder(context,TheDatabase.class,&quot;the_database_.xyz&quot;)
                        .allowMainThreadQueries() /* for brevity of demo */
                        .createFromAsset(&quot;anything.anything&quot;)
                        .build();
            }
            return INSTANCE;
        }
    }

- **NOTE** the parameter for the `createFromAsset` method. It MUST match the file name of the asset (and any sub-directories if placed in a sub-directory of the assets folder).

